citeinfo.title: Cottonwood Lake Study Area Invertebrate Surveys
A Systems Approach to Modeling the Effects of Climate and Land-use Change on Prairie Wetland Ecosystems

descript.abstract: This dataset contains macroinvertebrate sampling data for the wetlands in the Cottonwood Lake Study Area, Stutsman County, North Dakota.
descript.purpose: Record and identify macroinvertebrates present in the wetlands of the Cottonwood Lake Study Area in order to identify seasonal and interannual changes in macroinvertebrate community composition and facilitate a better understanding of the influence of natural and human modified climate variability on the diversity of prairie wetland ecosystems.
descript.supplinf: This dataset is part of the Missouri Coteau Wetland Ecosystem Observatory database that is a collection of abiotic and biotic data documenting biotic and abiotic responses to long-term climate and land-use change in the Prairie Pothole Region (PPR) of the U.S. The PPR has a naturally dynamic climate that is characterized by extended wet and dry periods, and its wetlands have spatially variable hydrologic and biotic traits. The Cottonwood Lake Study Area in Stutsman County, North Dakota contains wetlands representative of multiple positions along a hydrologic continuum, from groundwater recharge to discharge. The extensive history of data collection in the Cottonwood Lakes Study Area provides a unique opportunity to assess the impact of climate variability on ecosystem health and productivity.

spdom.descgeog: The Cottonwood Lake Study Area is located in a complex of Waterfowl Production Areas managed by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service in Stutsman County, North Dakota.

dataqual.logic: Data were checked for logical consistency upon entry into the table. Taxa were not repeated for any transect within a wetland per sampling effort. Species count attributes hold decimal values because large samples were split and taxonomic composition of some taxa estimated as a percentage of the total sample. Counts were then expanded to account for the number of splits and to be representative of the total sample.
dataqual.complete: This table includes data for each successful sampling effort. Data that were not recorded or were missing/lost are marked with NAs.

procstep.procdesc: Macroinvertebrate identification and counts were recorded on data sheets and transferred to an electronic spreadsheet. Data sheets were transferred via double entry by technicians. Double entered data sets were compared against each other and any detected errors were corrected.

method.methdesc: Aquatic macroinvertebrates were collected each month (April-September) from all wetlands at Cottonwood Lake Study Area containing water using vertically oriented funnel traps (Swanson 1978). Sampling was stratified to provide separate estimates of invertebrate biomass and abundance in all major vegetative zones of each wetland. Samples were collected at random locations along the 3 established transects in each wetland that were established earlier and used to collect other biotic and abiotic data (LaBaugh et al. 1987). The length of each vegetation zone as bisected by transects was measured and a computer-generated set of random numbers used to identify sample points for the collection of invertebrate samples in each vegetative zone. One sample was collected from each major vegetative zone from each transect. Data consist of counts by taxa.
Samples were taken back to the laboratory for macroinvertebrate identification. Total number of each taxa identified were recorded per sample.
